\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
\align block
This document presents recommended methods and settings for the atmospheric
 dispersion modelling system GRAL and the non-hydrostatic mesoscale wind-field
 model GRAMM.
 These recommendations are based on experience and insights gained during
 the quality assurance procedure (see the GRAL/GRAMM documentation reports)
 and practical applications.
 This document aims to help users to obtain reasonable results for a wide
 range of applications.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
This document supplements the detailed model descriptions found in the documents
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Documentation of the Lagrangian Particle Model GRAL (Graz Lagrangian Model)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Documentation of the prognostic mesoscale model GRAMM (Graz Mesoscale Model)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the documentation of the graphical user interface 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

GRAL Manual - GRAL Graphical User Interface
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Known limits and shortcomings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
In the current version of GRAL the following physical processes are not
 implemented
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Chemistry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
In the current version of GRAL the following shortcomings are known
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Sometimes unrealistically high concentrations occur at facades, probably
 because the reflexion and/or the well-mixed criterion are not treated well
 enough by the model.
 Thus, it is not recommended to use computed concentrations at facades of
 buildings/obstacles.
 At least one grid point shall be between the point of interest and the
 side wall of a building.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Due to the stepped resolution of terrain in GRAL simulations, stepped patterns
 may occur in the resulting concentration maps (see chapt.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Stepped-horizontal-concentration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for advice).
 
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Recommendations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
General hints for using GRAMM/GRAL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Roughness length
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:roughness"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 lists ranges for roughness lengths per land-use type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If running GRAL without GRAMM, one of these values representing the model
 domain may be input into the graphical user interface (GUI).
 When running GRAL in this way, the roughness length as defined in the GUI
 is used for the entire model domain.
 Even if buildings are taken explicitly into account in GRAL simulations,
 it is necessary to set a mean roughness length in such cases, except the
 option “Adaptive Roughness” is used.
 If GRAL is coupled with GRAMM, the user-defined land-use file and therefore
 spatially varying surface roughness lengths are imported from the GRAMM
 model.
 The prescribed roughness value in the GUI is not used in this case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the Adaptive Roughness option is used, the GUI roughness length defines
 the minimum surface roughness in the domain area, the specified Adatpive
 Roughness value defines the maximum surface roughness.
 The surface roughness is estimated based on buildings and vegetation areas.
 For vegetation with a height of up to 1 m, the height is interpreted as
 roughness length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optional file 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RoughnessLengthsGral.dat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 overrules the adaptive surface roughness algorithm and the GRAMM rouhness
 and defines the spatially varying surface roughness based on the values
 defined in this file.
 This file must be an ESRI ASCii raster file and the file must match the
 flow field raster (cell number, cell size).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When running GRAMM, the user may create a CORINE-based land-use file containing
 spatially non-homogenous roughness lengths.
 If GRAMM is used with the Adaptive Roughness option, the Adaptive Roughness
 is only used if it is higher than the GRAMM Roughness.
 When coupling with GRAMM, the Adaptive Roughness option should be used
 carefully (small maximum values).
\end_layout

