\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Determination of stability classes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is recommended to use a slightly modified form of the solar radiation
 delta-T (SRDT) method described in US-EPA (2000) to compute stability classes
 A-G (1 - 7).
 The method uses the surface layer wind speed (measured at or near 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m) in combination with measurements of total solar radiation during the
 day and a low-level vertical temperature difference ∆T at night.
 In order to distinguish between ‘DAYTIME’ and ‘NIGHTTIME’, it is recommended
 to use a threshold for solar radiation of 20
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

W/m² (note that instruments sometimes have offsets, thus a threshold of
 0
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

W/m² is not recommended).
 Note that GRAL uses figures instead of letters to assign stability classes
 (i.e.
 A = 1,…,G = 7).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Pasquill-Gifford-(P-G)-stability"

\end_inset

Pasquill-Gifford (P-G) stability categories
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

