\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Mesoscale wind field simulations with GRAMM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
General remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Currently, the standard procedure is as follows: a meteorological time series
 is classed as defined by the user.
 For each binned situation GRAMM calculates quasi steady-state solutions
 for the flow field.
 Using such simple meteorological input data for a mesoscale model means
 that large uncertainties in computed flow fields evolve due to unknown
 surface temperatures, soil temperatures, soil moisture distributions, snow
 cover, etc.
 For this reason, the following the following procedure is recommended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use an artificial wind rose (delivered with GRAMM) as meterological input
 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Artificial-wind-rose"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The artificial wind rose contains a variety of wind speed, wind direction
 and stability classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use a sufficient number of wind speed and wind direction classes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In mountainous areas the variability of the wind fields can be increased
 by using the sunrise Option
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Post-processing procedures are provided by the GUI
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
Re-order function:
\shape default
\bar default
 This function can be applied to any existing GRAMM wind field simulation.
 The procedure looks up every computed flow situation discriminating between
 stable, neutral, and convective conditions, and selects the best-fitting
 simulation for each classed meteorological situation.
 The re-order function can be used but is not further developed anymore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
Match-to-observation function:
\shape default
\bar default
 This function can be applied to any existing GRAMM wind field simulation.
 The procedure looks up every computed flow situation discriminating between
 stable, neutral, and convective conditions, and selects the best-fitting
 simulation for each classified meteorological situation.
 This function can be used for multiple meteorological observations at any
 location within the model domain.
 It enables the following modelling strategy: first, for a specific classificati
on scheme of wind speed, and -direction defined by the user, all theoretically
 possible situations are simulated, using an artificial, equally distributed
 wind rose.
 In a second step, these simulations are matched to any observational site
 within the model domain.
 Whenever new observations are available or a detailled evaluation is needed
 for a part of the model domain, these existing wind fields can again be
 matched and need not to be simulated again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Artificial-wind-rose"

\end_inset

Artificial wind rose
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/ArtificialWindrose.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The match-to-observation functional should be the preferred method in most
 GRAMM applications as it has the potential to improve simulation results
 enormously.
 Note that as wind-fields change after the match, stability classes will
 do so, too.
 Based on our experience, it might happen in less complex terrain, that
 the frequencies of each stability class throughout the model domain will
 deviate substantially from observed ones.
 Setting the weighting factors for each station used in the match function
 to a very low value, e.g.
 0.05 instead of the default value 1, increases the influence of stability
 classes compared to wind direction and wind speed.
 Weighting factors >1 lower the influence of the stability classes and increase
 the weigthing of wind speed and wind direction.
 Using the latest GRAMM and GUI (20.01 or later) version, the vectorial optimizat
ion method is preferred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Complex terrain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In the presence of complex terrain it is strongly recommended to apply GRAMM
 to get 3D wind fields as input for GRAL.
 GRAMM can take into account effects of drainage flows, slope winds, blocking-,
 channeling of flows, and re-circulation behind topographical elevations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
For regulatory purposes, GRAMM is driven by the same meteorological data
 as GRAL, i.e.
 a time series of wind speed, wind direction, and stability class at a certain
 height.
 It should be stressed that the interpretation of the meteorological input
 data depends on the size of the GRAMM modelling domain.
 Generally, the meteorological input data represents the so-called ‘large-scale
 forcing’, i.e.
 the forcing originating outside of the modelling domain.
 For instance, for areas ranging a few tens of kilometres, the large-scale
 forcing consists of synoptic-scale pressure systems and pressure gradients
 generated by for example, mountain ridges and their respective low-lands
 or between land surfaces and large water bodies.
 Typically, mountain-valley or land-see breeze systems have pressure gradients
 with length scales of more than 100 km.
 Therefore, if the model domain is larger than this, these pressure differences
 can be captured by the model.
 In this case, synoptic-scale pressure differences remain as the only large-scal
e force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The topography file used for GRAMM simulations 
\shape italic
\bar under
should not be smoothed
\shape default
\bar default
 at the boundaries for GRAMM versions 19.1.
 and higher.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is recommended to use the online functionality of the GUI, which helps
 to track the modelled flow fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In the case of numerical problems, one could try to reduce the 
\shape italic
\bar under
relaxation factors
\shape default
\bar default
 and/or the 
\shape italic
\bar under
maximum allowed time step
\shape default
\bar default
.
 By default, these values are 0.15 and 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

s regardless of the horizontal grid size.
 GRAMM automatically adjusts both factors to keep simulations numerically
 stable as far as possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The 
\shape italic
\bar under
integration time
\shape default
\bar default
 should be set in dependence on the size of the modelling domain and the
 intended physical phenomena to be simulated.
 For instance, if one attempts to simulate local phenomena such as slope
 winds or flow channelling, an integration time of one hour will be sufficient
 in most applications.
 However, if a user wishes to simulate mountain-valley wind systems or land-sea
 breezes, the integration time needs to be higher as the characteristic
 time scale of these phenomena are larger.
 An integration time of about 3 - 4 hours may often be suitable.
 Further, it is highly recommended that when simulating mountain-valley
 and land-sea winds, that the ‘sunrise option’ in the GUI is selected.
 This option invokes a transient computation of the sun’s incoming radiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
GRAMM adjusts the user-defined integration time in dependence on wind speed
 and stability in order to minimize the computational time.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Integration-times-[t]"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides an overview of the automatically adjusted integration times in
 GRAMM.
 As shown, when the sunrise option is selected by the user, the simulation
 time in convective conditions is always set to 6 hours regardless of the
 integration time chosen by the user.
 As already mentioned, the sunrise option should only be selected when simulatin
g mountain-valley or land-sea winds with very large model domains.
 In the case of stability classes 6 and 7, integration times in GRAMM are
 extended for low-wind-speed situations.
 In this model set-up cold-air drainage flows are expected to develop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Integration-times-[t]"

\end_inset

Integration times [t] in GRAMM in [s] in dependence on wind speed and stability
 class.
 The numbers in brackets apply when the sunrise option is invoked
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

