\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flat terrain applications of GRAMM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
There are also several reasons to apply GRAMM in relatively flat terrain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
To consider land-use changes in subsequent GRAL dispersion simulations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
To consider a wind-direction shift in the lower boundary layer due to surface
 roughness (Ekman shift) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
To include a proper transition between flat and complex terrain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In flat terrain, small forces introduced by the boundary conditions or numerical
 algorithms can have a large effect on simulated flow fields.
 Numerous tests (e.g.
 Wilhelm, 2017) have shown that the standard GRAMM set-up is not appropriate
 for simulations in very flat terrain.
 Therefore, the ‘flat terrain option’ is available in the GUI, where some
 settings in GRAMM are changed to better represent flat-terrain conditions.
 In particular, different boundary conditions at the lateral boundaries
 for momentum (homogenous von Neuman BC) is used.
 In addition, the numerical computation of air temperature and radiation
 is neglected.
 It is highly recommended to use the flat terrain option for the aforementioned
 modelling objectives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
General issues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is recommended to use a minimum of 15 vertical layers in GRAMM simulations,
 and a cell height of about 10 m for the first layer above ground level.
 Horizontal grid sizes can range from a few tens of metres up to several
 kilometres.
 The finer the horizontal resolution, the more prone GRAMM is to numerical
 instabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
How to check if GRAMM results are numerically stable?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
There are several options to track numerical stability of the model: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Once GRAMM is launched, the user can inspect the numerical values on the
 screen in the CMD-window (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Controlling-convergence-and"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 If these values increase constantly, numerical instability is likely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The online functionality of the GUI can be used to inspect simulated flow
 fields for every time step of the simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
When the computed wind speeds exceed 55
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s and 20
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s in the horizontal and vertical directions respectively, a ‘Problemreport.txt’
 will be written into the ‘Computation’ folder.
 The report is a simple text file, which can be viewed by any text editor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Mass divergence may increase during the simulation causing it to be larger
 at the end of the simulation than at the beginning.
 In this case, the ‘Problemreport.txt’ will include the following error message:
 ‘Final mass divergence is larger than initial mass divergence.
 Possible numerical instabilities detected for flow field: xx’, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Whenever GRAMM becomes numerically unstable, the computation core repeats
 the simulation with reduced maximum time steps and in the case of continuing
 instabilities, relaxation factors will be reduced.
 If the simulation is forced to repeat a weather situation (up to four attempts)
, the number right to the one indicating the weather situation is increased
 (e.g.
 28/2 is the second attempt of simulating weather situation 28).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
If the simulation is still unstable, the following recommendations may help
 to solve the problem: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Decrease the maximum allowed time step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Decrease the relaxation factors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Increase the number of cells at the boundaries over which topography is
 smoothed 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Increase the horizontal and/or the vertical grid spacing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Controlling-convergence-and"

\end_inset

Controlling convergence and numerical stability of mesoscale flow simulations
 with GRAMM
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/01GRAMM.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In some cases, the user may require a small modelling domain.
 Consequently, drainage flows might be underestimated or not simulated at
 all.
 This is because some of the hilly terrain causing drainage flows may be
 located outside of the model domain.
 The ‘catabatic forcing’ option may help to obtain better representation
 of drainage flows in such situations.
 In addition, the catabatic forcing can save CPU time in order to represent
 catabatic processes with smaller integration times.
 If possible however, it is recommended that the model domain is selected
 large enough to contain all important terrain characteristics playing a
 role in the development of drainage flows instead of using the 'catabatic
 forcing' option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Microscale flow field simulations with GRAL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Prognostic flow field model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The microscale flow field model in GRAL is a fully prognostic, non-hydrostatic
 model that takes into account the effects of buildings on dispersion.
 Thus, it is a very powerful tool to simulate flow around obstacles.
 However, the model can also be prone to numerical instabilities due to
 the complex, iterative-solution algorithm applied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In order to resolve obstacles with some accuracy, it is recommended to use
 a horizontal grid resolution below 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
 Best results are seen with grid sizes in the range of 2 – 4
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
 The vertical grid size for the first layer above ground should be in the
 range of 1 – 2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
 Vertical grid spacing below 1 m may lead to numerical instabilities.
 In addition, it is recommended to use the online functionality of the GUI
 to inspect flow fields during the simulation process.
 Alternatively, the user can analyse the GRAL flow fields when available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Generally, it can be stated that numerical instabilities can be avoided
 in most cases by increasing the vertical grid spacing or by decreasing
 the horizontal resolution.
 From experience, cubic-like grid cells (i.e.
 horizontal and vertical grid spacing are more or less equal) appear to
 ensure best numerical stability of the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In many cases, problems can be avoided by keeping the model domain boundaries
 free of any obstacles.
 It is highly recommended that no obstacles are placed near the boundaries
 of the model within an area of approximately 10 times the horizontal grid
 size.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
As GRAL has been thoroughly tested with the below set of parameter values
 prescribed in the GUI, it is not recommended to change these, as the model
 may become numerically unstable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The recommended set of parameter values is as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Number of vertical cells: 25 – 40 (depending on the max.
 height of obstacles) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Minimum iterations: 100 Maximum iterations: 500 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Roughness of building walls: 0.001
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
All other parameters related to the microscale flow field model are freely
 adjustable by the user.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
How is numerical instability identifiable by a user? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
There are several ways for detecting numerical instabilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Once GRAL is launched, the user can inspect the numerical values printed
 to the screen in the CMD-window right to the iteration number (see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Controlling-convergence-and-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 If these figures increase, then numerical instability is very likely, and
 one of the remedies as described above should be tried out.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Another way is to use the online functionality of the GUI, which allows
 for inspecting simulated flow fields every time step of the simulation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
GRAL itself writes a file named ‘Problemreport_GRAL.txt’ in the subdirectory
 ‘Computation’ whenever implausible wind speeds or non-convergence of the
 flow computation is detected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Controlling-convergence-and-1"

\end_inset

Controlling convergence and numerical stability for microscale flow simulations
 with GRAL, respectively
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/02GRAL.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
How to retrieve information about simulated flows with the microscale flow
 field model?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
In some cases, it may be of interest for users to retrieve information about
 the simulated microscale flow field.
 For instance, simulated wind speeds behind walls may be needed to compute
 the effect on fugitive dust emissions due to wind erosion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
As outlined in the GRAL manual, once receptor points are defined by the
 user, the time series of simulated flows at these receptor points is stored
 in the file named ‘GRAL_*NameOfReceptorPoint*.met’.
 This file is saved in the sub-directory ‘Metfiles’ after invoking the ‘Receptor
 points’ function (button) in the ‘Computation’ menu.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The below figures show a comparison between simulated flows by GRAMM in
 complex terrain at a specific point within a built-up area compared to
 subsequent GRAL simulations.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Deutschlandsberg"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the location of the air quality observations (Deutschlandsberg-A15)
 and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the observed and simulated wind-roses extracted from GRAMM and GRAL.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is noted that the GRAMM simulations were carried out with a rather coarse
 horizontal resolution (300 m), and cannot not take buildings into account.
 The GRAL simulations were performed with a resolution of 5 m and included
 buildings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that while GRAMM overestimates wind speeds at this site, GRAL is
 able to reproduce wind speeds well.
 In addition, wind directions are better captured by the GRAL microscale
 simulations.
 
\end_layout

