\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Diagnostic flow field model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
When running the model using the diagnostic option, the microscale flow
 around obstacles is computed on the bases of mass conservation only.
 GRAL evaluations clearly indicate that this approach is inferior to the
 prognostic option.
 Thus, it is not recommended to use this approach unless the size of the
 model domain prohibits the use of the prognostic flow field model or the
 prognostic model cannot be operated to get numerically stable results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Pollutant dispersion simulations with GRAL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
General
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Due to the turbulence parameterisations used in the model it is not recommended
 to apply GRAL for averaging times smaller than 300 seconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Due to the nature of Lagrangian particle models, computed pollutant concentratio
ns are prone to a sampling error.
 This error can be kept small when the number of particles is set high enough.
 A rough guide can be found in the user manual of the graphical user interface.
 However, it is recommended that the user checks the file ‘Logfile_GRALCore.txt’,
 which can be found the folder directory where GRAL has been launched.
 In the case of large model domains with a large numbers of sources, there
 may not be enough particles defined by the user to adequately represent
 all sources in the simulation.
 In these cases, GRAL automatically increases the number of released particles.
 However, if the total number of particles (as documented in the logfile)
 is more than 20 % higher than initially defined by the user, it is highly
 recommended to increase the total number of particles in the simulations
 and to re-run the simulations from the beginning.
 The following table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Particlenumber"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 lists the minimum number of particles that are automatically assigned by
 GRAL, if the total initial number of particles is too low.
 As of GRAL version 20.01 a file 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Receptor_Timeseries_Transient.txt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is written at the end of a calculation.
 This file contains the estimated statistical error for each receptor point
 in the last line.
 High error values indicate that too few particles were used in the simulation.
 A value NA (not available) means that no concentration at this receptor
 (no particle) has been counted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float table
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Particlenumber"

\end_inset

Minimum number of particles automatically assigned by GRAL in cases, where
 the total number of particles is too low for a good representation of all
 sources within the model domain
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

