\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Complex-terrain"

\end_inset

Complex terrain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
If terrain needs to be taken into account, GRAMM simulations must first
 be completed.
 These simulations – due to computational reasons – can generally be performed
 with a rather coarse horizontal resolution (e.g.
 50 - 1000
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m).
 For some applications, however, it might be necessary to capture important
 topographical details at a higher resolution.
 This can be achieved through the GUI, and by running GRAL after the GRAMM
 simulations have been completed.
 This approach is explained below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The user will need to prepare a topography file in ASCII format.
 If specific topographical features are important, the use of a high-resolution
 terrain dataset (e.g.
 1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m to 25
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m, depending on the application) is recommended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Once the GRAMM wind fields have been imported into the project, and the
 GRAL domain has been defined, the user can import the high-resolution topograph
y file using the menu entry ’File – Import – Original GRAL topography‘ in
 the GIS window.
 The GIS window indicates the topography height at the top right of the
 menu bar.
 The topography file must be larger than the chosen GRAL domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Alternatively, the user may tick the corresponding check box in the menu
 ‘Computation’ of the GUI before starting the GRAL simulation.
 Once the topography file has been selected, the GUI automatically generates
 a new topography file for use in GRAL.
 This functionality is illustrated in the example below.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf

\shape italic
\bar under
Example: Pollutant dispersion in the vicinity of a stone quarry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Three simulations (tests) were performed with different settings, as summarised
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Test-configurations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The same GRAMM wind fields for the area were imported for all three tests.
 The GRAMM domain had a horizontal resolution of 300 m.
 
\end_layout

