\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Test 2 method applied
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The topography and predicted concentrations for Test 1, Test 2 and Test
 3 are presented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The three figures show that the use of highly-resolved terrain data has
 a significant impact on modelled concentrations.
 The Test 1 plot (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) show simplified terrain patterns compared to the other tests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The Test 2 results (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) show a significant improvement in the representation of terrain in GRAL.
 It is important to note here that in the case of Test 2, there was almost
 no increase in the simulation time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Due to the ‘stepped’ sides of the stone quarry, recirculation zones and
 rather complex microscale flow patterns would probably occur.
 Thus, invoking the prognostic microscale flow field model in GRAL was the
 preferred choice and was included in Test 3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the prognostic option can only be invoked in the presence of buildings,
 which are not of interest in this case, a work-around is necessary to force
 GRAL to perform microscale flow simulations around the stone quarry.
 Up to the GRAL version 20.01, a single building could be placed in the GRAL
 model domain with a height of 0.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m (indicated by the black rectangle in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Clearly, such a low building has no effect on the flow itself, but simply
 invokes the prognostic flow model of GRAL in the area, where the building
 is placed.
 This resulted in complex flow fields within the quarry, as shown in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FlowFieldGRAL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Since the roughness of the ground may be changed by such a building, this
 method is no longer recommended!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather, as of version 20.01, a large sub-domain factor up to 1000 can be
 selected to force GRAL to calculate a large area prognostically.
 If you simply enter a building with a height of 2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m and a sub domain factor of 1000, a surrounding area of 2000
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m around the building is calculated prognostically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The corresponding concentration map is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Test-3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note, that the microscale flow field model in GRAL uses the roughness length
 of the building, so it may be necessary to adjust this value in the ‘GRAL
 Settings’ screen to represent the conditions of the area of interest.
 It is noted that simulation times increased in this case by about a factor
 of 10 relative to Tests 1 and 2.
\end_layout

