\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Stepped-horizontal-concentration"

\end_inset

Stepped horizontal concentration patterns in complex terrain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Due to the resolution of terrain in GRAL simulations (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-of-stepped"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), stepped patterns may occur in the resulting concentration maps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example-of-stepped"

\end_inset

Example of stepped resolution of terrain in GRAL
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/09.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
This problem can be mitigated in the GRAL configuration using the following
 approaches:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Avoiding setting the concentration grids at a height close to the ground.
 For example, in the ‘GRAL Settings’ screen, ensure that the first ‘heights
 above ground’ value is set to 2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m or higher.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Increasing the vertical dimension of concentration layers (in the ‘GRAL
 Settings’ tab).
 This will create a smoothing effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Reducing the vertical grid size of the microscale flow-field grid (e.g.
 setting the vertical thickness of the first layer to 1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m and using a low vertical stretching factor (e.g.
 1.0).
 With the new ‘Flexible stretching factor’ functionality, acceptable computing
 times can be maintained using small stretching factors for low heights
 and higher factors for greater heights above the ground
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Setting the horizontal grid resolution of the GRAL concentration grid to
 be larger (e.g.
 twice as much) than the horizontal grid resolution of the GRAL internal
 flow-field grid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Using one or more of the above approaches should result in a smoothing of
 the stepped concentration patterns.
 When visualising contours in the GUI, it is recommended that the low-pass
 filter option for concentration maps is applied.
 This option is available in the GUI ‘Layout Manager’ for contour maps and
 should be activated by default.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another (additional) option is to use the function ‘Low pass filter GRAL
 topography’ (and to save the filtered terrain afterwards) before the calculatio
n is started.
 This smoothes the terrain and helps to avoid isolated holes in the topography.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is generally advised that, when using terrain and evaluating concentration
 layers, the height of evaluation should be above the value set for ‘Vertical
 thickness of first layer’.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dispersion calculation for high stack sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Especially for dispersion calculations with high stacks, special attention
 must be paid to a sufficient number of particles.
 Otherwise, unrealistic concentration fields with strong concentration fluctuati
ons can occur near the ground.
 If you ask what defines a high stack: it depends - on the height, the exit
 velocity and the exit temperature of the exhaust gases and the distance
 to the receptor points.
 The higher the stack compared to the distance to the receptor points, the
 more important is the number of particles.
 From a stack height of 40
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m, special attention should be paid to the following points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following procedure is proposed for estimating the particle number:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, you need some receptor points which are located in the plume
 direction of the first dispersion situations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Steady state mode
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Copy the file meteopgt.all and edit the original file.
 Keep only a few situations within this file.
 Then start the calculation and wait until it is finished.
 You will find the estimated statistical uncertainty for each receptor point
 in the file 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Receptor_Timeseries_Transient.txt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The error should be below 20
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

% even after the calculation of only a few situations.
 If you like to analyze the concentration in certain weather conditions,
 the uncertainty (for a plume direction towards the receptor point) should
 be below 5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

%.
 If a receptor point lies within the plume direction and the error value
 is NA or above 25
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

%, the number of particles should be increased.
 Once the uncertainties are low enough, replace the meteogt.all file with
 the previously created copy and start the final calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Transient mode
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Copy the file mettimeseries.dat and edit the original file.
 Keep only a few weather situations within this file.
 Then start the calculation, wait until it is finished and check the file
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Receptor_Timeseries_Transient.txt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 like in the steady state mode.
 Afterwards replace the mettimeseries.dat file with the previously created
 copy and start the final calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the transient mode, the grid size of the concentration grid should
 not exceed 25x25
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m², because otherwise very high concentrations of the transient particles
 and thus additional numerical uncertainties will occur, especially when
 calculationg the dispersion of very high stack sources (above 80
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m).
 This is somewhat contradictory to the fact that large concentration grids
 should be used for high stack sources.
 If necessary, a higher particle number must be used in such cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Pollutant dispersion from road tunnels in GRAL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Effect of air being sucked in by the tunnel entrance of the opposite lane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Oettl et al.
 (2002) found that large amounts (up to 50
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

%) of tracer emitted from a tunnel portal were sucked in via the tunnel
 portal of the opposite lane.
 In GRAL it is recommended to define an area around tunnel portals were
 traffic enters a tunnel, to take this effect into account.
 Normally such areas are not very large (see example in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Oppositelane"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and extend more in the direction of traffic flowing into the tunnel portal
 rather than in the opposite direction.
 In order to account for this effect, the following steps are necessary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Define the area around the tunnel portal by digitizing a building (the height
 of the ‘building’ doesn’t matter) using the GIS functionality of the GUI
 (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Oppositelane"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Select the prognostic mode in the GUI’s ‘Project’ menu and then press the
 button ‘Building file’ in the ‘Computation’ menu (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Generating-the-‘buildings.dat’"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 A file named ‘buildings.dat’ will be generated in the subdirectory ‘Computation’.
 Rename this file to ‘tunnel_entrance.txt’.
 Ensure that no other real buildings have already been digitized with the
 GUI, as all coordinates in the file ‘tunnel_entrance.txt’ will be used by
 GRAL to remove particles up to a height of 5 m.
 Other buildings may be digitized following this step.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Oppositelane"

\end_inset

Defining the area around a tunnel entrance of the opposite lane 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/9echt.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Generating-the-‘buildings.dat’"

\end_inset

Generating the ‘buildings.dat’ file using the GUI
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/9a.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Effect of traffic at the opposite lane on the tunnel jet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It can be assumed that whenever a tunnel jet stream crosses the opposite
 lane it will be destroyed by the vehicle’s induced turbulence.
 In the GRAL model it is possible to define the areas of traffic at the
 opposite lanes as described in the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Define the area of the opposite lane by digitizing a building (the height
 of the ‘building’ doesn’t matter) using the GIS functionality of the GUI
 (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OppLaneArea"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 It is reasonable to limit the length of the area to about 100 - 200
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m as tunnel jets typically do not exceed this length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Select the prognostic mode in the GUI in the ‘Project’ menu, then press
 the button ‘Building file’ in the menu ‘Computation’ (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Generating-the-‘buildings.dat’"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The ‘buildings.dat’ file will be generated in the ‘Computation’ subdirectory.
 Rename this file to ‘opposite_lane.txt’.
 Make sure that no other real buildings have already been digitized with
 the GUI, as all coordinates in the file ‘opposite_lane.txt’ will be used
 by GRAL to remove particles up to a height of 4
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
 Other buildings may be digitized following this step.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:OppLaneArea"

\end_inset

Defining the area of the opposite lane (make sure no other buildings have
 been digitized yet)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename RecommendationsPictures/11.png
	width 13cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Tunnel portals at depressed level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Naturally the effects of the ambient wind on the tunnel jet are weaker given
 that the tunnel portal is situated below surface level.
 In principle there are two ways to simulate this in GRAL:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Obstacles (buildings) can be defined with heights equal to the depth of
 the depressed level where the tunnel portal is situated.
 An example (Kaisermuehlentunnel in Vienna) is given in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TunnelObstacles"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this case the heights of the receptor points M1 – M5 were set to 7.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m above ground, as they were placed 2.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m above ground in reality and the tunnel portal is situated 5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m below surface level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Use of high-resolution topographical data.
 Firstly, GRAMM simulations must be carried out using these data.
 Note that the horizontal resolution of GRAMM can be rather coarse.
 In the case of the Kaisermuehlentunnel, a horizontal resolution of 25
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m was chosen.
 Subsequently, when running GRAL, the option to use high resolution original
 topographical data must be selected in the GUI (as described in sect.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Complex-terrain"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TunnelTopo"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depicts topography (purple shading) and buildings (green contours) around
 the Kaisermuehlentunnel, Vienna.
 An additional, building with a height of 0.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m has been defined (large green square) to invoke the microscale, prognostic
 wind-field model of GRAL as outlined in sect.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Complex-terrain"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Receptors were placed as they were in the real world at 2.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m above ground.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Both, options 1) and 2) resulted in quite similar results for the Kaisermuehlent
unnel.
 However, the recommended method is the utilization of high-resolution terrain
 but with a caveat that the terrain must be of good quality and checked/filtered
 first before use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
