\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Odour dispersion simulations using GRAL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Odour dispersion simulations using GRAL aim to provide ‘odour-hours frequencies’
, which form the basis for judging annoyance or nuisance in an area (for
 the exact definition of an odour hour read for instance Oettl et al., 2018).
 In addition, the GUI supports the computation of percentiles of mean-hourly
 odour concentrations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is recommended to use the ‘concentration-variance’ model (Oettl and Ferrero,
 2017) for assessing odour-hours instead of a constant-factor model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Based on comprehensive investigations (Oettl et al., 2014) the following
 guidance is provided to ensure traceability and sensible results when predictin
g odour from animal husbandry operations using GRAL: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Odour emissions from natural ventilated animal stables should be considered
 an area source close to the building facade (where the windows are situated),
 1.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m above ground and with a vertical extension of 1.0
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Horizontal grid spacing should be in the range of 2 – 3
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m when modelling building downwash effects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The vertical grid spacing of the first cell above ground should not exceed
 3
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m, and the vertical stretching factor should not be larger than 1.05.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The elevation for the concentration grid should be 1.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m above ground and its vertical extension should be 1.0
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For computing annual odour hours, odour thresholds of 1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

OU/m³ should be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
It is recommended that odours from different species (pigs, poultry etc.)
 are not considered cumulative due to the different nature of the odours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
For all-in / all-out systems it is recommended to take into account the
 saw-tooth cycle of emissions.
 Otherwise constant odour emissions in time may be adequate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

